ood.database

Class DatabaseRecord

  • java.lang.Object
    • ood.database.DatabaseRecord

  • public abstract class DatabaseRecord
extends Object
    The database record class is a generic abstract class destinated to represent a database record with each of its fields. The user must inherit this class to declare a type of record. He must declare it into the correspondent table/class as a public class. Moreover, he must name the child class 'Record'. Every field which must be included into the database must have an annotation (Field, PrimaryKey, AutoPrimaryKey, RandomPrimaryKey, NotNull, Unique, ForeignKey). If no annotation is given, the corresponding field will not be added into the database. Note that the native types are always NotNull. Fields which have the annotation AutoPrimaryKey must be 'int' or 'short' values. Fields which have the annotation RandomPrimaryKey must be 'long' values. Fields which have the annotation ForeignKey must be DatabaseRecord instances. Never alter a field directly throw a function of the child class. Do it with the function Table.alterRecord(DatabaseRecord, java.util.Map). Moreover, the constructor of the child class must be protected with no parameter (if this constraint is not respected, an exception will be generated). So it is not possible to instantiate directly this class. To do that, you must use the function Table.addRecord(java.util.Map), or the function Table.addRecords(java.util.Map...). The inner database fields do not need to be initialized. However, fields which have no annotation (which are not included into the database) are not concerned.

    1.0
